### Enhanced Example Java Code

Here’s a more comprehensive example that showcases adding multiple instances to an `ArrayList`, accessing them, and demonstrating additional operations like sorting:

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.Comparator;

class MyClass {
    private String name;

    public MyClass(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "MyClass{name='" + name + "'}";
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList<MyClass> myList = new ArrayList<>();

        // Adding multiple instances
        myList.add(new MyClass("Banana"));
        myList.add(new MyClass("Apple"));
        myList.add(new MyClass("Cherry"));

        // Accessing elements by index
        System.out.println("Accessing the first object: " + myList.get(0));

        // Print all objects in the list
        System.out.println("Before sorting:");
        for (MyClass obj : myList) {
            System.out.println(obj);
        }

        // Sorting the list based on the name property
        Collections.sort(myList, Comparator.comparing(MyClass::getName));

        // Print all objects after sorting
        System.out.println("After sorting:");
        for (MyClass obj : myList) {
            System.out.println(obj);
        }
    }
}
```

