It looks like you're interested in handling button clicks for user confirmations, such as deleting an item, through a modal dialog in a JavaScript-based UI framework. Below, I'll provide a more detailed example using both vanilla JavaScript as well as a React implementation for better clarity.

### Example: Modal Confirmation in Vanilla JavaScript

Here's a simple way to implement a confirmation dialog using vanilla JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Confirmation Modal</title>
    <style>
        /* Basic styles for the modal */
        .modal {
            display: none;
            position: fixed;
            top: 0;
            left: 0;
            width: 100%;
            height: 100%;
            background-color: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
        }
        .modal-content {
            background: white;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<button id="deleteButton">Delete Item</button>

<div id="confirmationModal" class="modal">
    <div class="modal-content">
        <h2>Are you sure you want to delete this item?</h2>
        <button id="confirmButton">Yes</button>
        <button id="cancelButton">No</button>
    </div>
</div>

<script>
    function confirmAction() {
        return new Promise((resolve) => {
            const modal = document.getElementById('confirmationModal');
            modal.style.display = 'flex';

            document.getElementById('confirmButton').onclick = () => {
                resolve({ isConfirmed: true });
                modal.style.display = 'none';
            };

            document.getElementById('cancelButton').onclick = () => {
                resolve({ isConfirmed: false });
                modal.style.display = 'none';
            };
        });
    }

    document.getElementById('deleteButton').onclick = () => {
        confirmAction().then((result) => {
            if (result.isConfirmed) {
                console.log("Action confirmed. Proceed with deletion.");
                // Call your deletion logic here
            } else {
                console.log("Action canceled. No deletion performed.");
            }
        });
    };
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure**: The modal structure is defined in HTML. It's hidden by default and only displayed when needed.
2. **CSS Styles**: Basic styles are applied to center the modal and give it a simple appearance.
3. **JavaScript Logic**: The `confirmAction` function shows the modal and returns a promise that resolves based on the user's choice. The modal is displayed when the delete button is clicked.

